## Work Classification

Before starting, ask: **"Is this 1 task or 3+ related tasks?"**

### Single Task

```javascript
task = save_task({title: "Fix validation bug in handlers.go", status: "in_progress"})
// Do the work
add_progress_log({task_id, who: "claude", what: "Fixed validation in handlers.go:234"})
update_task_status({task_id, status: "done"})
```

**One-call shortcut:** `save_task`, `update_task`, and `update_task_status` accept an optional inline `progress_log: {who, what}` that writes the log in the same call. Halves round-trips for the common "do work + log it" pattern:
```javascript
update_task_status({
  task_id,
  status: "done",
  progress_log: {who: "claude", what: "Fixed validation in handlers.go:234, all tests green"}
})
```

**Optimistic concurrency:** task / plan / document writes accept `if_version: N`. Stale writes return a 409-style conflict with the current version embedded for retry. Use this when multiple agents may be writing the same project.

**Typed relationships + external blockers:**
```javascript
// supersedes: mark OLD-1 as superseded by NEW-1
task_dependency({action: "add", task_id: "OLD-1", depends_on: "NEW-1", type: "supersedes"})
get_task_chain({task_id: "OLD-1", relationship_type: "supersedes"})

// External (non-task) blockers — inline on save_task / update_task (replace-all semantics)
save_task({
  project_id: "{{PROJECT_ID}}",
  title: "Ship feature X",
  external_blockers: [
    {reason: "Blocked on legal review", contact: "legal@example.com", eta: "2026-04-20T00:00:00Z"}
  ]
})
```

### 3+ Related Tasks — Create a Plan First

**The 3-Task Rule:** When you're about to create the third related task, stop. Create a plan first.

**Sequence matters:** Plan → Document → Tasks → Link → **Verify the wave structure**.

```javascript
// 1. Create plan
plan = save_plan({
  plan_id: "plan-auth-system",
  title: "User Authentication System",
  status: "in_progress",                         // or "draft" — see Complex Work below
  problem: "No user authentication",
  goal: "JWT-based auth with refresh tokens",
  approach: "Fiber middleware + PostgreSQL",
  estimated_duration: "3-4 hours"
})

// 2. Document IMMEDIATELY
doc = save_document({
  document_id: "doc-auth-plan",
  project_id: "{{PROJECT_ID}}",
  title: "Auth System - Implementation Plan",
  doc_type: "plan_details",
  content: `
# Goal
[Specific deliverable]

# Approach
[Technical strategy, stack, patterns]

# Task Breakdown
1. Task one - ~30min
2. Task two - ~20min
3. Task three - ~25min

# Success Criteria
- [ ] Measurable criterion 1
- [ ] Measurable criterion 2
`
})

// 3. Create tasks under the plan
task1 = save_task({plan_id: plan.plan_id, title: "JWT middleware", status: "todo", estimated_days: 0.5})
task2 = save_task({plan_id: plan.plan_id, title: "Login endpoint", status: "todo", estimated_days: 0.25, blocked_by: [task1.task_id]})
task3 = save_task({plan_id: plan.plan_id, title: "Token refresh", status: "todo", estimated_days: 0.5, blocked_by: [task2.task_id]})

// 4. Link document to all tasks
link_document({
  document_id: doc.document_id,
  task_ids: [task1.task_id, task2.task_id, task3.task_id]
})

// 5. VERIFY the wave structure — the killer view at this step
get_plan({plan_id: plan.plan_id, detail: "ascii"})
// Returns a server-rendered wave diagram + critical_path + estimated_remaining_days.
// Read it like a smoke test: do the dependency edges produce the wave structure
// you expected? Is the critical path the longest arm? Is anything you thought
// would parallelize actually serial? Fix edges before writing code.
```

### Complex Work (Unclear Scope)

**Old guidance: "Create a parent task FIRST, then plan, then create subtasks."**
**New guidance: don't.** A parent "umbrella" task duplicates the plan's role and creates audit-trail noise. The plan IS the umbrella. Use it.

**Canonical move: file a draft plan first, scope inside it, promote when ready.**

```javascript
// 1. File the plan in draft state — the working surface for scoping
plan = save_plan({
  plan_id: "plan-feature-x",
  title: "Feature X",
  status: "draft",                  // signals "scoping in flight"
  problem: "Brief framing — refine as you learn",
  goal: "Best current understanding of the deliverable",
  approach: "TBD"                   // OK to leave loose; you're scoping
})

// 2. Capture decisions / open questions in a linked document. The doc is
//    where the structured thinking lives — risks, alternatives considered,
//    open questions. The plan stays terse.
doc = save_document({
  document_id: "doc-feature-x-design",
  project_id: "{{PROJECT_ID}}",
  title: "Feature X — Design",
  doc_type: "plan_details",
  content: "# Open Questions\n- ..."
})
link_document({document_id: doc.document_id, plan_id: plan.plan_id})

// 3. As decisions firm up, file tasks under the plan with proper blocked_by
//    edges. You are NOT creating an umbrella task that wraps them — the plan
//    is the wrapper.
task1 = save_task({plan_id: plan.plan_id, title: "Concrete sub-step 1", status: "todo"})
// ...

// 4. Promote when ready
update_task({plan_id: plan.plan_id})  // applied to plan
save_plan({plan_id: plan.plan_id, status: "in_progress"})

// 5. Verify wave structure (same as 3-Task Rule above)
get_plan({plan_id: plan.plan_id, detail: "ascii"})
```

**Why no umbrella task?** A parent task that "tracks the whole effort" duplicates what the plan already does: it has a status, an owner, dependencies, progress logs, and linked documents. Creating both means you maintain both — and they drift. When the plan ships, the parent task either gets closed redundantly or hangs around as cruft. Skip it.

