## Verifying Wave Structure

After creating a plan with tasks + dependencies, verify the structure before writing code. Two complementary views:

```javascript
// Killer view: server-rendered ASCII wave diagram
get_plan({plan_id: "plan-x", detail: "ascii"})
// Returns: ascii string + waves[] + next_available + next_wave_blockers
//          + components + critical_path + estimated_remaining_days
//          + estimate_coverage
//
// Output looks like:
//   Wave 0: ★T0(○ {{PROJECT_ID_UPPER}}-1)
//   Wave 1: T1(○ {{PROJECT_ID_UPPER}}-2) T2(○ {{PROJECT_ID_UPPER}}-3)
//   Wave 2: ★T3(○ {{PROJECT_ID_UPPER}}-4)
//
//   Next available: {{PROJECT_ID_UPPER}}-1
//   Legend: ○ todo
//   ★ = on critical path
//
// Read it like a smoke test:
//   - Do the wave indices match your mental model of the dependency depth?
//   - Is the critical path (★) the path you'd predict?
//   - Are tasks you expected to parallelize actually in the same wave?
//   - Are tasks you expected to serialize actually in different waves?
// If anything's off, fix the edges with task_dependency() before writing code.

// Structured view: same data without rendering
get_execution_waves({plan_id: "plan-x"})
// Use when you want to consume the wave structure programmatically (for
// example: pick the highest-priority task in wave 0 to start).

// Render knobs (passed to either tool)
get_plan({plan_id: "plan-x", detail: "ascii", with_titles: true})  // titles inline
get_plan({plan_id: "plan-x", detail: "ascii", style: "ascii"})     // [X] [/] [ ] glyphs (terminal/log safe)
get_plan({plan_id: "plan-x", detail: "ascii", width: 120})         // wider rendering
```

`load_session_state(include_plan_context=true)` ALSO returns this rendering inline as `plan_ascii` for the session's `current_plan_id` — so a fresh instance gets the wave structure for free at boot. No extra call needed at session start.

